'''George Ames Plimpton''' (March 18, 1927 – September 25, 2003) was an American journalist, writer, [[literary editor]], actor and occasional amateur sportsman. He is widely known for his [[sports journalism|sports writing]] and for helping to found ''[[The Paris Review]]'', as well as his patrician demeanor and [[transatlantic accent|accent]]. He was also famous for "[[New Journalism|participatory journalism]]" which included competing in professional sporting events, acting in a [[Western (genre)|Western]], performing a [[Stand-up comedy|comedy]] act at [[Caesars Palace]] in [[Las Vegas]], and playing with the [[New York Philharmonic Orchestra]]<ref name=Aldrich72>''The Best of Plimpton'', p. 72</ref> and then recording the experience from the point of view of an amateur.

==Early life==
Plimpton<ref name="Plimpton1">{{cite news|last=Severo|first=Richard|title=George Plimpton, Urbane and Witty Writer, Dies at 76|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/26/obituaries/26CND-PLIM.html|date=September 26, 2003|accessdate=May 25, 2010}}</ref> was born in New York City on March 18, 1927, and spent his childhood there, attending [[St. Bernard's School]] and growing up in an apartment duplex on Manhattan's [[Upper East Side]] located at 1165 [[Fifth Avenue]].<ref name=Aldrich18>Aldrich, p. 18</ref> During the summers, he lived in the [[hamlet]] of [[West Hills, New York|West Hills, Huntington, Suffolk County]] on [[Long Island]].<ref name=Aldrich18/><ref name=Aldrich18/>

He was the son of [[Francis T. P. Plimpton]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/07/31/obituaries/francis-tp-plimpton-82-dies.html|title=Obituary: Frances T. P. Plimpton, 82, Dies|work=The New York Times|first=David|last=Margolick|date=July 31, 1983}}</ref> and the grandson of Frances Taylor Pearsons and [[George Arthur Plimpton]].<ref name=Chase140>Chase, p. 140</ref><ref name=Chase110>Chase, p. 110</ref><ref name=Chase86>Chase, p. 86</ref><ref name=Chase85>Chase, p. 85</ref><ref>Calvin Gay Plimpton and Priscilla G. Lewis were the parents of [[George Arthur Plimpton]]. see Chase pp. 85–86</ref><ref name="Miller31-33">Miller, pp. 31–33</ref> His grandfather was the founder of the Ginn publishing company and a philanthropist.<ref>[http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=plimpton&GSiman=1&GScid=91204&GRid=26734414& George Arthur Plimpton profile], findagrave.com; accessed October 26, 2015.</ref> His father was a successful corporate lawyer and partner of the law firm [[Debevoise and Plimpton]] who was appointed by President [[John F. Kennedy]] as U.S. deputy ambassador to the [[United Nations]], serving from 1961 to 1965.<ref name=Aldrich19>Aldrich, p. 19</ref>

His mother was Pauline Ames,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/04/17/obituaries/pauline-a-plimpton-93-author-of-works-on-famed-relatives.html|title=Obituary: Pauline A. Plimpton, 93, Author Of Works on Famed Relatives|work=The New York Times|first=Robert McG.|last=Thomas, Jr.|date=April 17, 1995}}</ref> the daughter of botanist [[Oakes Ames (botanist)|Oakes Ames]] and artist [[Blanche Ames Ames|Blanche Ames]]. Both of Plimpton's maternal grandparents were born with the surname Ames; his mother was the granddaughter of [[Medal of Honor]] recipient [[Adelbert Ames]] (1835-1933), an American sailor, soldier, and politician, and [[Oliver Ames (governor)|Oliver Ames]], a US [[politician|political figure]] and the [[List of Governors of Massachusetts|35th]] [[Governor of Massachusetts]] (1887–1890). She was also the great-granddaughter on her father's side of [[Oakes Ames]] (1804–1873), an industrialist and congressman who was implicated in the [[Crédit Mobilier of America scandal|Crédit Mobilier railroad scandal]] of 1872; and Governor-General of New Orleans [[Benjamin Butler (politician)|Benjamin Franklin Butler]], an [[Law of the United States|American lawyer]] and [[Politics of the United States|politician]] who represented [[Massachusetts]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]] and later served as the [[List of Governors of Massachusetts|33rd]] [[Governor of Massachusetts]].<ref>He was widely reviled for years after the war by [[Southern United States|Southern]] whites, who gave him the nickname "Beast Butler." He is also credited with saving [[Baltimore, Maryland]] during the Civil War.</ref>

George had three siblings: Francis Taylor Pearsons Plimpton Jr., Oakes Ames Plimpton,<ref>{{cite web|last=Plimpton |first=Oakes Ames |title=Milton at the Midpoint of the Last Century: One Collection of Memories |publisher=Milton Academy |date=Spring 2007 |url=http://www.milton.edu/news/upload/spring-2007-mm.pdf |accessdate=May 14, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528132833/http://www.milton.edu/news/upload/spring-2007-mm.pdf |archivedate=May 28, 2010 |df=mdy }}</ref> and Sarah Gay Plimpton.

==Education==
Plimpton attended [[St. Bernard's School]], [[Phillips Exeter Academy]] (from which he was expelled just shy of graduation), and [[Daytona Beach]] Mainland High School, where he received his high school diploma<ref>{{cite web|url=http://306.exeter.edu/publications/exeter/spring_02/success.html|title=How Failing at Exeter made a Success of George Plimpton|work=Phillips Exeter Academy Bulletin|date=Spring 2002|archivedate=September 10, 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060910010551/http://306.exeter.edu/publications/exeter/spring_02/success.html}}</ref> before entering [[Harvard College]] in July 1944. He wrote for the ''[[Harvard Lampoon]]'', was a member of the [[Hasty Pudding Club]], Pi Eta, the Signet Society, and the [[Porcellian Club]]. He majored in English. Plimpton entered Harvard as a member of the Class of 1948, but did not graduate until 1950 due to intervening military service. He was also an accomplished [[birdwatcher]].{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}

Plimpton's studies were interrupted by military service lasting from 1945 to 1948, during which he served as a [[tank]] driver in Italy for the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]]. After graduating from Harvard, he attended [[King's College, Cambridge|King's College]] at [[Cambridge University]] in England. He studied there from 1950 to 1952 and graduated with third class honors, BA in English.<ref>{{cite book|last=Aldrich|first=Nelson|title=George, being George|pages=80}}</ref>

==Career==

===Literary criticism===
{{unreferenced section|date=October 2015}}
In 1953, Plimpton joined the influential literary journal ''The [[Paris Review]]'', founded by [[Peter Matthiessen]], [[Thomas H. Guinzburg]], and [[Harold L. Humes|Harold L. "Doc" Humes]], becoming its first editor in chief. This periodical has carried great weight in the literary world, but has never been financially strong; for its first half-century, it was allegedly largely financed by its publishers and by Plimpton. Two articles by [[Richard Cummings (writer)|Richard Cummings]], "An American in Paris" (''The American Conservative'') and "The Fiction of the State" (''Lobster''), disclosed that the [[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] provided funds for ''The Paris Review'', using publisher [[Sadruddin Aga Khan]]'s foundation as a conduit, and that Plimpton was an "agent of influence" for the CIA. Peter Matthiessen took the magazine over from Humes and ousted him as editor, replacing him with Plimpton, using it as his cover for his CIA activities. [[Jean Stein]] became his co-editor. Plimpton was associated with the literary magazine in Paris, ''Merlin'', which folded because the State Department withdrew its support.{{Why|date=October 2015}} Future [[Poet Laureate]] [[Donald Hall]], who had met Plimpton at Exeter, was Poetry Editor. One of the magazine's most notable discoveries was author and screenplay writer [[Terry Southern]], who was living in Paris at the time and formed a lifelong friendship with Plimpton, along with writer [[Alexander Trocchi]] and future classical and jazz pioneer [[David Amram]].{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}

===Sports journalism===
{{refimprove section|date=October 2015}}
Outside the literary world, Plimpton was famous for competing in professional sporting events and then recording the experience from the point of view of an amateur.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} In 1958, prior to a post-season exhibition game at Yankee Stadium between teams managed by [[Willie Mays]] (National League) and [[Mickey Mantle]] (American League), Plimpton pitched against the [[National League]]. His experience was captured in the book ''Out of My League''. (He intended to face both line-ups, but tired badly and was relieved by [[Ralph Houk]].) Plimpton sparred for three rounds with [[boxing]] greats [[Archie Moore]] and [[Sugar Ray Robinson]], while on assignment for ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}

In 1963, Plimpton attended preseason training with the [[Detroit Lions]] of the [[National Football League]] as a backup [[quarterback]], and ran a few plays in an intrasquad scrimmage. These events were recalled in his best-known book ''[[Paper Lion]]'', which was later adapted into a feature film starring [[Alan Alda]], released in 1968. Plimpton revisited pro football in 1971,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5AkRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=xecDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6673,5627547|title=Plimpton trying football again|work=The Free-Lance Star|first=Bill|last=Buttram|date=August 19, 1971}}</ref> this time joining the [[Baltimore Colts]] and seeing action in an exhibition game against his previous team, the Lions. These experiences served as the basis of another football book, ''Mad Ducks and Bears'', although much of the book dealt with the off-field escapades of football friends such as [[Alex Karras]] and [[Bobby Layne]]. Another sports book, ''Open Net'', saw him train as an [[ice hockey]] goalie with the [[Boston Bruins]], even playing part of a [[National Hockey League]] preseason game.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}

Plimpton's ''The Bogey Man'' chronicles his attempt to play professional golf on the [[PGA Tour]] during the [[Jack Nicklaus|Nicklaus]] and [[Arnold Palmer|Palmer]] era of the 1960s. Among other challenges for ''Sports Illustrated'', he attempted to play top-level [[Contract bridge|bridge]], and spent some time as a [[tightrope walking|high-wire circus performer]].{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} Some of these events, such as his stint with the Colts, and an attempt at stand-up comedy, were presented on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television network as a series of specials.

In 1994 Plimpton appeared several times in the [[Ken Burns]] series ''[[Baseball (TV series)|Baseball]]'' where he shared some personal baseball experiences as well as other memorable events throughout the history of baseball.<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/kenburns/baseball/ Baseball: A film by Ken Burns], ''PBS'', 2010, Retrieved December 27, 2013.</ref>

===Sidd Finch===
In the April 1, 1985 issue of ''Sports Illustrated'', Plimpton pulled off one of the greatest [[April Fools' Day]] pranks of all time. With the help of the [[New York Mets]] organization and several Mets players, Plimpton wrote a convincing account of a new unknown pitcher in the Mets spring training camp named [[Sidd Finch|Siddhartha Finch]] who threw a baseball over 160&nbsp;mph, wore a heavy boot on one foot, and was a practicing [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] with a largely unknown background.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/vault/issue/43450/76/2|title=SI Vault – April 1, 1985 – Page 76|website=www.si.com|accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref> The prank was so successful that many readers believed the story, and the ensuing popularity of the joke resulted in Plimpton writing an entire book on Finch.

===Other writing===
{{unreferenced section|date=October 2015}}
A personal friend of the New England Sedgwick family, Plimpton edited ''Edie: An American Biography'' with [[Jean Stein]] in 1982. He also appeared in a brief interview footage about [[Edie Sedgwick]] in the DVD extra for the film ''[[Ciao! Manhattan]]''. In addition, he appeared in the [[PBS]] ''[[American Masters]]'' documentary on [[Andy Warhol]]. Plimpton also appeared in the closing credits of the 2006 film, ''[[Factory Girl (film)|Factory Girl]]''.

Between 2000 and 2003, Plimpton wrote the [[libretto]] to a new opera Animal Tales, commissioned by [[Family Opera Initiative]], with music by [[Kitty Brazelton]] directed by [[Grethe Barrett Holby]]. He wrote, "I suppose in a mild way there is a lesson to be learned for the young, or the young at heart – the gumption to get out and try one's wings."

===Acting===
Plimpton also appeared in a number of feature films as an extra and in cameo appearances. He had a small role in the [[Academy Award|Oscar]]-winning film ''[[Good Will Hunting]]'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2003/9/29/legendary-humorist-poonster-dies-at-76/|title=Legendary Humorist, Poonster Dies at 76 {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-04}}</ref> playing a psychologist. Plimpton played [[Tom Hanks]]'s antagonistic father in ''[[Volunteers (film)|Volunteers]]''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Volunteers|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/volunteers/|language=en|accessdate=2018-02-04}}</ref> He was also notable for his appearance in television commercials during the early 1980s, including a memorable campaign for [[Mattel]]'s [[Intellivision]]. In this campaign, Plimpton aggressively touted the superiority of Intellivision video games over those of competitors such as the [[Atari 2600]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.openculture.com/2014/12/george-plimpton-pitches-video-games-for-the-mattel-intellivision.html|title=George Plimpton, Paris Review Founder, Pitches 1980s Video Games for the Mattel Intellivision|work=Open Culture|access-date=2018-02-04|language=en-US}}</ref>

He hosted [[Disney Channel]]'s ''[[Mouseterpiece Theater]]'' (a ''[[Masterpiece Theatre]]'' spoof which featured Disney cartoon shorts). In the "[[I'm Spelling as Fast as I Can]]" episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', he hosts the "Spellympics" and attempts to bribe Lisa Simpson to lose with the offer of a scholarship at a [[Seven Sisters (colleges)|Seven Sisters College]] and a hot plate; "it's perfect for soup!"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/the-simpsons/im-spelling-as-fast-as-i-can-181997/cast/|title=The Simpsons: I'm Spelling As Fast As I Can|last=TV.com|website=TV.com|access-date=2018-02-04}}</ref> He had a recurring role as the grandfather of [[John Carter (ER)|Dr. Carter]] on the long-running [[NBC]] series ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/09/27/arts/george-plimpton-author-and-editor-is-dead-at-76.html|title=George Plimpton, Author And Editor, Is Dead at 76|last=Severo|first=Richard|date=2003-09-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-02-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He also appeared in an episode of the NBC sitcom ''[[Wings (1990 TV series)|Wings]]''.

Plimpton appeared in the 1989 documentary ''The Tightrope Dancer'' which featured the life and the work of the artist [[Vali Myers]]. He was one of her original supporters and had published an article about her work in ''The Paris Review''. He also appeared in the 1996 documentary ''[[When We Were Kings]]'' about the "Rumble in the Jungle" 1974 Ali-Foreman Championship fight opposite [[Norman Mailer]] crediting [[Muhammad Ali]] as a poet who composed the world's shortest poem: "Me? Whee!!"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1975/6/9/professor-muhammed-ali-delivers-lecture-poems/|title=Professor Muhammed Ali Delivers Lecture; Poems and Parables Fill Talk on Friendship {{!}} News {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-04}}</ref>

Plimpton was a member of the cast of the [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] TV series ''[[A Nero Wolfe Mystery]]'' (2001–02). In 2013, the documentary ''[[Plimpton! Starring George Plimpton as Himself]]'', directed by Tom Bean and Luke Poling, was released. The film used archival audio and video of Plimpton lecturing and reading to create a posthumous narration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pbs.org/wnet/americanmasters/george-plimpton-film-plimpton-starring-george-plimpton-as-himself/2946/|title=George Plimpton {{!}} Full Film {{!}} American Masters {{!}} PBS|date=2014-05-16|work=American Masters|access-date=2018-02-04|language=en-US}}</ref>

===Fireworks===
Plimpton was a demolitions expert in the post-[[World War II]] Army. After returning to New York from Paris, he routinely fired off [[fireworks]] at his evening parties.<ref name="CSMp7">{{cite web |url= http://www.csmonitor.com/1981/0813/081355.html/%28page%29/7|title= George Plimpton|last= McBride|first= Stewart|date= August 13, 1981|website= The Christian Science Monitor |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102170239/http://www.csmonitor.com/1981/0813/081355.html/%2528page%2529/7|archivedate= November 2, 2013|deadurl=no|accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref>

His enthusiasm for fireworks grew, and he was appointed Fireworks Commissioner of New York by Mayor [[John Lindsay]],<ref name="CSMp7"/><ref name="PeoplePunk">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20074425,00.html|title=George Plimpton, Still Burning His Punk at Both Ends, Finds a Sport in Which He Can Sparkle|last=Dowling|first=Kevin|date=August 27, 1979|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102175150/http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20074425,00.html|archivedate=November 2, 2013|deadurl=yes|accessdate=2013-11-02|df=mdy-all}}</ref> an unofficial post he held until his death.<ref name="Plimpton1"/>

In 1975, in [[Bellport, New York|Bellport, Long Island]], Plimpton attempted to break the record for the world's largest firework.<ref name="HeroicFailure">{{cite book|last=Pile|first=Stephen|title=[[The Book of Heroic Failures]]: The Official Handbook of the Not Terribly Good Club of Great Britain|publisher=Futura|year=1979|isbn=0708819087|page=73|chapter=Two: Off Duty}}</ref><ref name="CSMp6">{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1981/0813/081355.html/%28page%29/6|title=George Plimpton profile|last=McBride|first= Stewart|date=August 13, 1981|website=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102170502/http://www.csmonitor.com/1981/0813/081355.html/%2528page%2529/6|archivedate=November 2, 2013|deadurl=no|accessdate=2013-11-02}}</ref><ref name="SIScorecard19760223">{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1090772/4/index.htm|title=SI Vault: Scorecard – 02.23.76|date=February 23, 1976|editor-last=Creamer|editor-first=Robert W.|website=Sports Illustrated|page=4|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102170658/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1090772/4/index.htm|archivedate=November 2, 2013|deadurl=no|accessdate=2013-11-02|quote=But Fat Man sat heavily on the ground, sizzled, smoked and then exploded, leaving a gaping hole 10 feet deep and 35 feet wide.}}</ref> His firework, a [[Roman candle (firework)|Roman candle]] named "Fat Man",<ref name="HeroicFailure"/><ref name="CSMp6"/><ref name="SIScorecard19760223"/> weighed {{convert|720|lb|kg}}<ref name="HeroicFailure"/> and was expected to rise to {{convert|1000|ft|m}}<ref name="SIScorecard19760223"/> or more<ref name="HeroicFailure"/> and deliver a wide starburst.<ref name="CSMp6"/> When lit, the firework remained on the ground and exploded, blasting a crater {{convert|35|ft|m}} wide and {{convert|10|ft|m}} deep.<ref name="SIScorecard19760223"/> A later attempt, fired at [[Cape Canaveral]], rose approximately {{convert|50|ft|m}} into the air and broke 700 windows in [[Titusville, Florida]].<ref name="CSMp7"/>

With [[Felix Grucci]], Plimpton competed in the 16th International Fireworks Festival in 1979 in [[Monte Carlo]]. After several problems with transporting and preparing the fireworks, Plimpton and Grucci became the first competitors from the United States to win the event.<ref name="PeoplePunk"/> Plimpton later wrote the book ''Fireworks'', and hosted an [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] Home Video with the same name featuring his many fireworks adventures with the Gruccis of New York in Monte Carlo and for the 1983 Brooklyn Bridge Centennial.<ref name="Plimpton1"/>

===Parodies of Plimpton's career===
A November 6, 1971, cartoon in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' by [[Whitney Darrow Jr.]] shows a cleaning lady on her hands and knees scrubbing an office floor while saying to another one: "I'd like to see George Plimpton do ''this'' sometime." In another cartoon in ''The New Yorker'', a patient looks up at the masked surgeon about to operate on him and asks, "Wait a minute! How do I know you're not George Plimpton?"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,942286,00.html|title=George Plimpton: The Professional Amateur|work=Time|first=Gerald|last=Clarke|date=September 21, 1970}}</ref> A feature in ''[[Mad Magazine]]'' titled "Some Really Dangerous Jobs for George Plimpton" spotlighted him trying to swim across [[Lake Erie]], strolling through New York's [[Times Square]] in the middle of the night, and spending a week with [[Jerry Lewis]].<ref>{{cite journal
|title=Some Really Dangerous Jobs For George Plimpton
|url=https://www.comics.org/issue/93957/#toc_1033012
|journal=Mad Magazine |volume=157 |date=March 1973 |pages=37–39
|author1=Arnie Kogen
|author2=Jack Davis }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Plimpton was married twice.<ref name="Plimpton1"/> His first wife, whom he married in 1968<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/03/29/archives/phrnpfon-drops-sinies-for-doubles.html|title=Plimpton Drops Singles for Doubles|work=The New York Times|first=Charlotte|last=Curtis|date=March 29, 1968}}</ref> and divorced in 1988, was Freddy Medora Espy, a photographer's assistant. She was the daughter of writers [[Willard R. Espy]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/02/25/arts/willard-espy-who-delighted-in-wordplay-is-dead-at-88.html|title=Obituary: Willard Espy, Who Delighted In Wordplay, Is Dead at 88|work=The New York Times|first=Robert McG.|last=Thomas, Jr.|date=February 25, 1999}}</ref> and Hilda S. Cole, who had, earlier in her career, been a publicity agent for [[Kate Smith]] and [[Fred Waring]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/01/26/obituaries/hilda-cole-espy-writer-83.html|title=Hilda Cole Espy, writer, 83|work=The New York Times|date=January 26, 1995}}</ref> They had two children: Medora Ames Plimpton and Taylor Ames Plimpton, who has published a memoir entitled ''Notes from the Night: A Life After Dark''.
[[File:Ann Moller, Herb Caen and George Plimpton.jpg|thumb|left|Plimpton with Herb Caen and Ann Moller in 1993]]
In 1992, he married Sarah Whitehead Dudley, a graduate of [[Columbia University]] and a freelance writer.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/01/05/style/george-plimpton-writer-and-editor-is-wed-to-sarah-w-dudley-a-writer.html|title=George Plimpton, Writer and editor, Is Wed to Sarah W. Dudley, a Writer|work=The New York Times|date=January 5, 1992}}</ref> She is the daughter of James Chittenden Dudley,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/24/business/james-c-dudley-77-investment-adviser.html|title=Obituary: James C. Dudley, 77, Investment Adviser|work=The New York Times|date=September 24, 1998}}</ref> a managing partner of Manhattan-based investment firm Dudley and Company, and geologist Elisabeth Claypool. James and Elisabeth established the {{convert|36|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[Highstead Arboretum]] in [[Redding, Connecticut]]. George and Sarah were the parents of twin daughters Laura Dudley Plimpton and Olivia Hartley Plimpton.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}

===Friendship with Robert Kennedy===

At Harvard, Plimpton was a classmate and close personal friend of [[Robert Kennedy]].{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} Plimpton, along with former [[decathlon|decathlete]] [[Rafer Johnson]] and [[American football]] star [[Rosey Grier]], was credited with helping wrestle [[Sirhan Sirhan]] to the floor when Kennedy was assassinated following his victory in the 1968 California [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] primary at the former [[Ambassador Hotel (Los Angeles)|Ambassador Hotel]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=EventAccount>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,900110-3,00.html|title=A Life On The Way To Death|work=TIME|date=1968-06-14|accessdate=2008-04-27| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080501101804/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,900110-3,00.html| archivedate=May 1, 2008 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>

==Death and tributes==
Plimpton died on September 25, 2003, in his New York City apartment from an apparent heart attack. He was 76.<ref name="Plimpton1"/>

An oral biography titled ''George, Being George'' was edited by [[Nelson W. Aldrich Jr.]], and released on October 21, 2008. The book offers memories of Plimpton from among other writers, such as [[Norman Mailer]], [[William Styron]], [[Gay Talese]] and [[Gore Vidal]], and was written with the cooperation of both his ex-wife and his widow.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}

In the movie ''[[Plimpton! Starring George Plimpton As Himself]]'', the writer [[James Salter]] said of Plimpton that "he was writing in a genre that really doesn't permit greatness."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/05/23/186016416/plimpton-a-fond-look-at-a-man-of-letters|title='Plimpton!': A Fond Look At A Man Of Letters|author=Ian Buckwalter|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=May 23, 2013}}</ref>

In 2006, the musician [[Jonathan Coulton]] wrote the song entitled "A Talk with George", a part of his 'Thing A Week' series, in tribute to Plimpton's many adventures and approach to life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jonathancoulton.com/wiki/A_Talk_With_George|title=A Talk with George – JoCopedia, the Jonathan Coulton wiki|website=www.jonathancoulton.com|accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>

Plimpton is the protagonist of the semi-fictional ''George Plimpton's Video [[Falconry]]'', a 1983 ColecoVision game postulated by humorist [[John Hodgman]] and recreated by video game auteur Tom Fulp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newgrounds.com/portal/view/571422|title=Plimpton's Video Falconry|website=Newgrounds.com|accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref>

Researcher and writer Samuel Arbesman filed with [[NASA]] to name an asteroid after Plimpton; NASA issued the certificate [[7932 Plimpton]] in 2009.<ref name="Arbesman 2009">{{Cite news|last=Arbesman|first=Samuel|title=Naming the Sky: The true story of one man's quest to give George Plimpton a permanent presence in orbit|newspaper=The Boston Globe|date=September 27, 2009|url=http://www.boston.com/bostonglobe/ideas/articles/2009/09/27/naming_the_sky|accessdate=October 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=7932+Plimpton 7932 Plimpton (1989 GP)], ssd.jpl.nasa.gov; accessed October 26, 2015.</ref>

