'''John Alexander "Alex" Tyler''' (April 7, 1848 &ndash; September 1, 1883) was the second son of [[President of the United States|President]] [[John Tyler]] and his second wife, [[Julia Gardiner Tyler]]. He was born at the Tyler estate, [[Sherwood Forest Plantation]], near [[Charles City, Virginia]].<ref name="Sherwood Forest Genealogy">{{cite web |url=http://www.sherwoodforest.org/Genealogy.html |title=Genealogy of John Tyler at Sherwood Forest Plantation |author= |date=January 27, 2009 |location=Charles City, VA, USA |publisher=[[Sherwood Forest Plantation|Sherwood Forest Plantation Foundation]] |accessdate=February 25, 2012}}</ref>
==During the Civil War== After the death of his father, at age 14 he ran away from home to enlist in the [[Confederate States Army]], but was rejected as too young. His mother, [[Julia Gardiner Tyler]], eventually allowed him to join the [[Confederate States Navy]] because it had a lesser casualty rate than the Confederate Army. However, Tyler spent most of his time on a ship quarantined due to [[yellow fever]] and left naval service in 1864. After attending college for three months, he left and joined the First Virginia Battalion of Artillery under General [[Robert E. Lee]], just prior to Lee's surrender at [[Appomattox Court House National Historical Park|Appomattox]], which effectively ended the war.<ref name="Quinn-Musgrove">{{cite book |last1=Quinn-Musgrove |first1=Sandra L |last2=Kanter |first2=Sanford |title=America's royalty : all the presidents' children |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D6egBFIqZJQC&dq=editions:gcQKbp0nHrgC&hl=en&q=%22john%20alexander%20tyler%22#v=snippet&q=%22john%20alexander%20tyler%22&f=false |accessdate=February 25, 2012 |year=1995 |origyear=1983 |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]] |location=Westport, CT, USA |isbn=978-1-56750-893-2 |oclc=501482396 |pages=64–66 }}</ref><ref name=Todd>{{cite book |last1=Todd |first1=Charles Burr |authorlink1=Charles Burr Todd |editor1-first=Henry Reed |editor1-last=Stiles |editor1-link=Henry Reed Stiles |title=In olde New York; sketches of old times and places in both the state and the city |url=https://archive.org/stream/inoldenewyorkske00toddch#page/174/mode/2up |accessdate=February 25, 2012 |type= |edition= |series=The Grafton historical series |year=1907 |publisher=The Grafton press |location=New York, NY |oclc=3985699 |pages=174–175 }}</ref>
==In Europe== In 1865, he and his brother, [[David Gardiner Tyler]], traveled to [[Germany]] to attend college, where he studied in [[Karlsruhe|Carlsruhe]], [[Baden]] and [[Freiberg, Saxony]]<!--[[Technische Universität Bergakademie Freiberg]]?--> to become a [[Mining engineering|mining engineer]]. Still in Germany in 1870 at the outbreak of the [[Franco-Prussian War]], Tyler enlisted in the [[Prussian Army]] and joined the [[1st Guards Uhlans|First Uhlan]] regiment under the command of King [[John of Saxony]]. He served with distinction in the occupation of [[France]] in 1871.<ref name="Quinn-Musgrove"/><ref name=Todd/>
==Later years== In 1873, Tyler returned to the United States and attempted to find work as a mining engineer near [[Salt Lake City]], but was unable to find a position, probably due to the [[Long Depression|Depression of 1873–79]]. Although he did find a job with a railroad, the salary did not allow him to meet his debts, and he had financial problems until he married a wealthier [[Cousin#Explanation chart|third cousin]], [[Sarah Griswold Gardiner]],<ref name="Quinn-Musgrove"/><ref name=LIHS>{{cite journal |author=Long Island historical society |journal=The Long Island historical journal |page=16 |location=Stony Brook, NY |publisher=Dept. of History, [[Stony Brook University|State University of New York at Stony Brook]] |issn=0898-7084 |oclc=754563051 |accessdate=February 25, 2012 |title=Julia's son John Alexander Tyler, who married Sarah (Sally) Griswold Gardiner, a third cousin ... |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EAoqAQAAMAAJ&q=%22John+Alexander+Tyler%22+OR+%22John+Alex+Tyler%22&dq=%22John+Alexander+Tyler%22+OR+%22John+Alex+Tyler%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=6HZJT8HcJIOSiQLc_-DcDQ&ved=0CIkCEOgBMCU }}</ref> on August 5, 1875.<ref name=Welles>{{cite book |last1=Welles |first1=Albert |title=History of the Buell family in England : from the remotest times ascertainable from our ancient histories, and in America, from town, parish, church and family records ... |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ma4aAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22John%20Alexander%20Tyler%22%20OR%20%22John%20Alex%20Tyler%22&pg=PA303#v=onepage&q=%22John%20Alexander%20Tyler%22%20OR%20%22John%20Alex%20Tyler%22&f=false |accessdate=February 25, 2012 |series=Genealogy & local history, G32 |year=1881 |publisher=Society Library |location=New York, NY |oclc=181016428 |at=p. 303, 6. V. 5. (col. 2)|quote=Sarah Griswold Gardiner, daughter of Hon. Samuel Buell Gardiner, of [[Gardiners Island|Gardiner's Island]], was married at East Hampton, L. I., on Thursday, 5th August, 1875, to John Alexander Tyler, son of the late President of the United States, John Tyler, of Virginia. }}</ref> President [[Rutherford B. Hayes]] later appointed him as a surveyor for the [[United States Department of the Interior]].<ref name="Bergen">{{cite web | url=http://deadpresidents.tumblr.com/post/12845262761/presidential-offspring?print | title=Dead Presidents - Presidential Offspring | work=Dead Presidents | accessdate=February 25, 2012 | last=Bergen | first=Anthony}}</ref> In 1883, at 35 years old, Tyler died of a fever while working as a mining engineer in [[New Mexico]].<ref name=Todd/>
